issue.title: Can't find address when using `блок` instead of `бл.`
issue.body:
<!-- Note: this template is for reporting problems with searching. If you have found an issue with the data, you need to report/fix the issue directly in OpenStreetMap. See https://www.openstreetmap.org/fixthemap for details. -->

## What did you search for?
`блок 717 ж.к. люлин 7`
https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%BA%20717%20%D0%B6.%D0%BA.%20%D0%BB%D1%8E%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BD%207
<!-- Please try to provide a link to your search. You  can go to https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org and repeat your search there. If you originally found the issue somewhere else, please tell us what software/website you were using. -->

## What result did you get?
Nothing

## What result did you expect?
The same as when searching for `бл. 717 ж.к. люлин 7`
https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=%D0%B1%D0%BB.%20717%20%D0%B6.%D0%BA.%20%D0%BB%D1%8E%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BD%207

**When the result missing completely:**
https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/26667926

## Further details

`блок` is the long version of `бл.`. It is also listed in https://github.com/osm-search/Nominatim/blob/master/settings/icu-rules/variants-bg.yaml.

comment.body: It's a Bulgarian abbreviation that should be known to Nominatim: https://github.com/osm-search/Nominatim/blob/master/settings/icu-rules/variants-bg.yaml#L4

issue.title: Improve handling of Russian house numbers
issue.body:
The Russian community has an agreement on the format of house numbers, but it is slightly different from how addresses are usually written. Example: ["5 литера Б"](https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/ui/search.html?q=%D0%A1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BA%D1%82-%D0%9F%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D1%83%D1%80%D0%B3%2C+%D0%9A%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%8F+%D1%83%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0%2C+5+%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B0+%D0%91&accept-language=ru&countrycodes=ru) is ["5 литБ"](https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/ui/search.html?q=%D0%A1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BA%D1%82-%D0%9F%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D1%83%D1%80%D0%B3%2C+%D0%9A%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%8F+%D1%83%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0%2C+5+%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%91&accept-language=ru&countrycodes=ru) in OSM. This can be fixed by client-side preprocessing, but I think it should be done by the search server.
Most common values (dots are optional):
| Full | Abbreviations | OSM | Example |
| ------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------- |
| дом  | д. | - | 42 |
| корпус  | корп. / кор. / к.  | к | 42 к1 |
| литера  | литер / лит.  | лит | 42 литА |
| строение  | стр. / с.  | с | 42 с1 |
| сооружение | соор. | соор | 42 соор1 |
| флигель | флиг. / фл. | фл | 42 фл1 |

In addition, the search will fail if input string contains additional data such as [room number](https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/ui/search.html?q=%D0%A1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BA%D1%82-%D0%9F%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D1%83%D1%80%D0%B3%2C+%D0%9A%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%8F+%D1%83%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0%2C+5+%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%91%2C+%D0%BA%D0%B2.+1&accept-language=ru&countrycodes=ru). Perhaps, we should create a list of tokens that can be deleted?

streamline SQLAlchemy DB schema

Remove all information not strictly used by the frontend as well as
any index information. This will make it easier to create a SQLite
database from the schema.
add skeleton code for convert function
add exporting of SQLite table

make lookup call work with sqlite

Includes porting unit tests.
make details API work with sqlite incl. unit tests
make status API work with sqlite incl. unit tests
try future annotations to resolve Generics compatibility
actions: enable sqlite testing
make reverse API work with sqlite
add indexing support for DWithin and intersects for sqlite
trim all coordinate output to 7 digits

enable BDD tests for sqlite databases

The database must currently be created by hand and the name handed
in via -DAPI_TEST_DB='sqlite:...'.

make code work with Spatialite 4.3

Transfer is_address_point into SQLAlchemy function, so that
json.has_key() can use the older json_extract() function.
And work around broken Distance function.

remove type info from SQLALchemy condition functions

A boolean type makes the SQLite dialect produce a costruct like
'func() = 1' in WHERE condition. While syntactically correct, it tends
to confuse the query planer.

restrict geometry size for SQLite

pull_request.title: Add support for SQLite DBs in frontend: reverse
pull_request.body:
This is the first part of enabling Nominatim to be run from a SQLite (or rather SpatialLite) database.

The major changes are:

* add a new CLI function `nominatim convert` to dump an existing PostGIS database into an SQLite file,
* adapt the API functions reverse(), details() and lookup() to work with SQLite,
* change unit tests for these API functions, so that they are run against SQLite and PostGIS respectively
* change BDD API tests so that they can be run against a SQLite database (SQLite file needs to created manually by running nominatim convert against the API tests database right now)

CI does run the unit tests for SQLite but not the BDD tests.

SQLite support is highly experimental and currently undocumented. To try it out, use the new convert function to create a databse. Then set the database DSN to `sqlite:dbname=<filename>` to use it. It also works with the web frontend and `nominatim serve` when using one of the Python engines.

Differences between PostgreSQL and SQLite are hidden behind custom SQLAlchemy functions, so  the code should not interfere with normal operations. If other interference shows up in production, I reserve the right to pull the code out again.

issue.title: Include indoor elements in results
issue.body:
Hello,
Is it possible to think about the opportunity of integrating indoor-related features in search results ? For example, if I'm looking to find this [element](http://www.openstreetmap.org/way/396967067), I will type something like `master sigat, rennes`, and expect to find the given element. Instead, [no result is returned](http://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/search.php?q=master+sigat%2C+rennes).
Cordially.

The city hospital first and 4 hospitals nearby 😄

Only hospitals nearby.

- [hospital near annecy](https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=hospital%20near%20annecy#map=17/45.93224/6.11754) return in second position an hospital in Bonneville, far from Annecy.
- [hospital annecy](https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=hospital%20annecy#map=15/45.9356/6.1321) seem fine 😎 
- [hôpital d'annecy](https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=hôpital%20d%27annecy#map=17/45.93224/6.11754) give results in Bonnville too 😞

issue.title: Some valid postcodes with country code in the name do not pass validation
issue.body:
## What did you search for?

All postcodes from Isle of Man (IM) and Jersey (JE) do not pass postcode validation. As a result, a search for a valid postcode IM9 4LY returns nothing:
https://www.openstreetmap.org/search?query=IM9%204LY
even though the postcode exists in OSM data:
https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/396520136

The issue is caused by postcode normalisation function which strips the country code from the postcode. It does not work correctly when a valid postcode is prefixed by its country's country code. This can be fixed by removing the country code from the postcode pattern in country_settings.yaml config file, as is done for Anguilla, Andorra, Cayman Islands, Saint Lucia, Latvia, Moldova, Saint Vincent and British Virgin Islands. However, such approach makes the validation less accurate, as it lets the invalid postcodes (without the two letter prefix) be accepted as valid ones. Additionally, there are at least two countries in which postcodes can start with country code, but don't have to:
- Malta, postcodes in Mtarfa town start with MTF
- Brunei - some postcodes start with BN: https://postal-codes.cybo.com/brunei/
These cannot be treated by fixing the output format, though I can't tell if these cases currently exist in OSM data or not. 

Strangely, the postcode QA map does not show the affected postcodes for Isle of Man and Jersey, even though they must have been rejected from search index as illegal:
https://nominatim.org/qa/#map=9.43/54.17/-4.32&layer=postcode_bad_format

## What result did you get?

Nothing

## What result did you expect?

Valid postcode

**When the result missing completely:**

I expect the postcode from these nodes to be searchable: 
https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/396520136
https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/493311642
https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/591317991


## Further details

I prepared a generic fix for this issue, by including the country regex in normalization regex. This way the country code is stripped when it is part of the postcode pattern only in case it is duplicated. (e.g. IM IM9 4LY)
